{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17488622","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17488622"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:49:52+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:49:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"494"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"494","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/494"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.83,0.03,0.05,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"494"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107926"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"494","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/494"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"494"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90344"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1717"},{"type":"tags","id":"2076"},{"type":"tags","id":"9022"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"949"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7326"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7532"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12547"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14760"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14943"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16276"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33406"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40248"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107926","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107926"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 64-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a one-hour history of sudden loss of vision in his left eye. He has experienced two or three similar episodes over the past two months, but they resolved rapidly on their own. He has a medical history of hypertension, osteoarthritis and gastro-oesophageal reflux disease. His regular medications include amlodipine, paracetamol, and pantoprazole.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 78/min, blood pressure 142/88 mmHg, respiratory rate 14/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. His right eye examination is unremarkable but there is no perception of light in his left eye. The left anterior chamber is clear and extraocular movements are normal. Fundoscopic examination of the left eye is undertaken (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following investigations is most likely to establish the underlying cause of the current problem?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["24-hour Holter monitoring","Carotid artery duplex ultrasound","Serum lipid profile","MRI brain","Temporal artery duplex ultrasound"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient\u0027s symptoms and the signs on fundoscopy are consistent with central retinal artery occlusion (CRAO), which presents with sudden, painless, and unilateral vision loss. The pale retina with a cherry red spot on fundoscopy is characteristic of this condition. The previous episodes of transient vision loss suggest amaurosis fugax, which can precede CRAO.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECarotid artery duplex ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate investigation in this case. Carotid atherosclerosis is the most common cause of CRAO, and carotid imaging is essential in the systemic evaluation of these patients. This non-invasive investigation can identify significant carotid stenosis or plaque that may be the source of emboli causing the retinal artery occlusion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E24-hour Holter monitoring\u003C/strong\u003E may be useful in detecting paroxysmal atrial fibrillation. However, cardiac evaluation is typically reserved for patients in whom carotid disease has been ruled out. Since carotid atherosclerosis is the most common cause, carotid imaging takes priority in the initial workup.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Eserum lipid profile\u003C/strong\u003E may be helpful in assessing the patient\u0027s overall cardiovascular risk but is unlikely to establish the immediate cause of the current problem. It would be part of a broader workup rather than the most crucial investigation for determining the aetiology of CRAO.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMRI brain\u003C/strong\u003E would be indicated if there were concerns about intracranial pathology, such as stroke or intracranial bleeding. However, the patient\u0027s symptoms and examination findings are localised to the eye, making this investigation less relevant for evaluating the cause of CRAO.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETemporal artery duplex ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E is used to investigate giant cell arteritis, which can cause vision loss. However, this condition typically presents with additional symptoms such as headache, scalp tenderness, and jaw claudication, which are not present in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFollowing carotid imaging, if no significant carotid disease is identified, cardiac evaluation including echocardiography and Holter monitoring would be appropriate to investigate cardiac sources of emboli.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Central retinal artery occlusion presents with sudden, painless unilateral vision loss and a pale retina with a cherry red spot on fundoscopy.","Carotid atherosclerosis is the most common cause of central retinal artery occlusion, making carotid imaging the priority investigation.","Transient ischaemic attacks of the eye (amaurosis fugax) can precede central retinal artery occlusion."],"references":["Cugati S, Varma DD, Chen CS, Lee AW. Treatment Options for Central Retinal Artery Occlusion. Curr Treat Opt Neuro. 2013;15:63-77. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3553407/","Mehta N, Marco RD, Goldhardt R, Modi Y. Central Retinal Artery Occlusion: Acute Management and Treatment. Curr Ophthalmol Rep. 2017;5(2):149-159. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5642921/","Sharma N, Ooi JL, Sharma D, Nguyen E. Sudden loss of vision - a case study. Aust Fam Physician. 2013 Jan-Feb;42(1-2):48-50. PMID: 23529461. Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/afp/2013/januaryfebruary/sudden-loss-of-vision/","American Academy of Ophthalmology [Internet]. 2017 [cited 2025 Jul 4]. Diagnosis and Management of Central Retinal Artery Occlusion. Available from: https://www.aao.org/eyenet/article/diagnosis-and-management-of-crao"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90344"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"494"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18048"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18048","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18048"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/4452831a-18f5-4872-ad01-4d68ac9e1c56.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/4452831a-18f5-4872-ad01-4d68ac9e1c56.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90344","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/90344"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-04T21:39:05+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-04T21:40:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"494"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107926"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"8","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/8"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc41","name":"Ophthalmology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationsh